name: 1,3-Diphenylpropane-1,3-dione

The basic unit for comparison can be benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C. The introduction of two phenyl groups increases the melting point due to the enhancement of the crystalline structure and the increase in molecular weight. Each phenyl group may contribute around +30 to +50°C. Additionally, the dione functional group introduces a carbonyl group, which can participate in hydrogen bonding and rigidify the structure, estimated at around +10°C. The presence of two methoxy groups can also contribute to the melting point due to the increase in molecular weight and the capacity for hydrogen bonding, estimated at around +5°C each.
